A First Guide to Programming in R

2022-01-25

1 How To Write and Run Scripts

Throughout this group, we’ll be using two different kinds of documents. To follow along with the examples, create a new script document in RStudio by using the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+Shift+N (Windows) or Command+Shift+N (Mac). Alternatively, clicking the green plus sign on the white sheet of the paper on the top left of the RStudio notebook will also allow you to create a new script file. From there, to learn code, I would encourage you to type the code snippets in the new script file rather than copy-pasting (I personally find typing things myself to be more useful – your mileage may vary).

To run code in R, you can highlight lines in your script document, then use the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+Enter (Windows) or Command+Enter (Mac). There’s also a “Run” button towards the top-left corner of the text window. Your code outputs should then appear in the Console window below, and any new variables you make will show up in the Environment window to the right.

2 The Basics

This is a short guide to learning how to code in R! If you are already familiar with coding, feel free to skip this section, as it will just cover the basics. Otherwise, read on!

2.1 Variables

A variable stores some kind of data within your program. A variable takes one of many types of data; in R, you don’t have to specify the type. The most relevant data types (most of which are applicable to other languages) are:

  • NULL/NA: an undefined or “nothing” value.
  • bool: a true or false value. bool stands for Boolean values. For example, 1 < 10 would yield a TRUE value, since 1 is less than 10. Note that in R, both TRUE and T mean “true”, and likewise FALSE and F mean “false”. The capitalization is important (you’ll get an error if you write True or false, for example)!
  • numeric or double: some kind of number. Note that in R, numeric is a catch-all, while in other languages there is a clear distinction/incompatibility betweenints (integer values, e.g. 3) and floats (floating point/decimal values, e.g. 1.5).
  • string: a text value. These are defined using single OR double quotes, for example 'QBIO' or "quantitative biology". It’s a matter of preference; I mostly use double quotes out of habit (C++).- - vector: Vectors contain data all of the same data. You create a vector by enclosing elements with c(); for example, c(1, 2, 10) or c("a", "red", "b")
  • list: some kind of ordered values. for example [[1, 2.0, "three"]]. As you can see, you can mix and match data types in R in a list.
  • data.frame and matrix: essentially 2D lists or tables.
  • factors: these are categorical variables in R (non-numerical variables in a sense). You’ll need to specify if a variable is a factor for some purposes, such as in plotting. In general, strings in your data will be factors, such as “old” or “young”, “sweet”/“sour”/“bitter”, etc.

You can declare a variable in R in one of two (mostly) equivalent ways: with = or <-. Note that the # denotes a comment in R, which is text that is written but not executed.

var_string = "red" # one way to declare a variable, with an equals
var_num <- 3 # another way to declare a variable, with the arrow
var_vector = c(1, 2, 3) # a vector -- see more later
var_list = list(var_string, var_vector, 82)  # a list can have basically anything in it

2.1.1 A Note on Naming Variables

There is no convention on how to format your variable names, but the most important rule is to keep them just descriptive enough to describe the information contained. For example, these are examples of acceptable ways to name a variable (from best to fine):

sum_of_ages = sum(ages)  # very clear, underscore are good
sumOfAges = sum(ages)  # different formatting, but just as good
AgeSum = sum(age)  # also good, though sometimes frowned upon to capitalize the first letter
sum.age = sum(age)  # it's ok to use periods in a name in R, not good in other languages

Here’s some not-as-good ways:

sum = sum(ages)  # avoid naming variables after functions, unclear what the sum is
s = sum(ages)  # not descriptive, very unclear
sumofages = sum(ages)  # hard to read
SUMOFAGES = sum(ages)  # reserve caps for very important constants in your code
blargh = sum(ages)  # funny but bad (some people code like this)

As you can see, there’s a million ways to name a variable. Don’t worry about it too much: keep things descriptive and concise, but I would err on the side of descriptive. Just be consistent and make sure things are readable.

2.2 Functions

Functions, on a very basic level, perform repeatable actions on the parameters passed to them. Functions have three important components:

  • Name.
  • Parameters. A function can have number of parameters (including 0), depending on how it’s defined.
  • Return value. It’s return value is what it outputs. In R, you can return either no values or one value.

To call a function, use the syntax funcname(arg1, arg2, etc.). You’ve seen functions before in math class, like \(\sin(\pi)\) – the input is \(\pi\), the name is \(\sin\), and the output is whatever the \(\sin\) value is (0 in this case). You’ve also seen functions with multiple parameters before like addition, x + y: the function name is +, the two parameters are x and y, and the return value is whatever x + y is – you just substitute the values in. In R, you can add two numbers as follows (note that programming languages implement +; this is just a contrived example to show the syntax):

x = 5
y = 7
sum(x, y)
## [1] 12
x + y  # this is the same
## [1] 12

You can also save a function’s output (its return value) to a variable. For example, if I wanted save those numbers, I could do the following:

z = sum(x, y)
z
## [1] 12

2.3 Writing Functions

Writing functions is extremely important, as it makes code more concise, easier to read, and more reusable. The way you write a function in R is as follows:

function_name = function(arguments){
  code goes here
  return(something)
}

To dissect the syntax: you define a function using the function keyword, and you put all keywords within the parentheses. Since functions often have more than one line, you use curly braces ({ }) to define its contents. Finally, at the end of the function, you may have a return statement, which is essentially its output. Again, not all functions have a return statement. For example, if I needed graph a bunch of different parabolas a lot of times, I could write the following function (remember that \(y = ax^2 + bx + c\). Also, you don’t need to understand this code for now):

graph_parabola = function(a, b, c){
  curve(a*x^2 + b*x + c, xlim = c(-10, 10), ylim = c(-10, 10), 
        col = "blue", ylab = "y")
  # there is no return statement -- the output is in the plot window!
}

graph_parabola(2, 4, 3) # much easier than typing the above code!

graph_parabola(1, 0, 0)  # easy to replicate!

The main takeaway is that you can simply call the function graph_parabola(a, b, c)instead of specifying a bunch of parameters in plot. In general, you should write a function whenever you call the same functions with the same parameters on different inputs. From anecdotal evidence, people tend to underuse functions while performing data analysis and just end up copy and pasting code. Your analysis will be a lot clearer to other people and to future you if you use them more often!

Exercise 2.3 Write a function called quad_form that accepts three parameters (a, b, c) and return the positive solution of the quadratic formula (so return \(x = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\)). A few hints:

  • The square root command is sqrt() (equivalently, you can raise something to the 0.5 power with the carat).
  • Order of operations does work as you’ve been taught in school (for operators of the same priority, they are evaluated left-to-right). However, you need to be explicit when writing multiplication, i.e. you need to use the asterisk to show that you are multiplying two numbers together. (x*y is necessary; x y doesn’t work).
  • As good practice, it’s best to explicitly return the value you calculate if you want to be able to assign the function output to another variable. R will actually return the output of the last line that you write so you don’t need to type return(), but R is an exception and this won’t work in other languages.

2.4 Logic and Control Flow

Now that we know how to store data and manipulate it with functions, how do you decide when to call functions? Control flow allows you to determine which chunk of code to run under which situations.

Logical statements evaluate either to TRUE or FALSE (they are bools). In general, you will use comparison operators Here are a list of the most commonly-used ones:

Operator Explanation
== Equals to (e.g. "red" == "red" is TRUE; 1 == 2 is FALSE)
!= Not equals to
< Less than
> Greater than
<= Less than or equal to
>= Greater than or equal to
%in% Present in a vector/list (e.g. 2 %in% [[1, 2, 3]] is TRUE)

All of these except the last (%in%) are universal to most other programming languages, so be sure to understand them!

You can also perform more operators on these bool comparisons. There are three main operations: and, or, and not:

Operator Explanation
& (And) TRUE if both left and right are TRUE
| (Or) TRUE if either left or right are TRUE
! (Not) flips TRUE to FALSE, and vice versa.

(note: in R, if you use && and || on a vector, you will only evaluate the first value, rather than getting an entire vector. If you want a vectorized logical operator, use & and | — see the section on vectors for more information. In general, you’ll want to use the single character version of these operators. in R.)

The if keyword is the main control flow keyword that you will use. If the statement within the if code block (i.e. the part within the curly braces) is TRUE, then it will run.

The else and else if keywords go with the if keyword. They are somewhat self-explanatory: if the if statement is TRUE, do what is in the if block; otherwise, do what is in the else block. The else if keyword is related to the else keyword, in that it will happen if the if statement is false AND the else if statement is true. Can you predict the output of the following code block? Then, to check your answer, copy and paste the code into your document and run it!

if (1 > 2){
  print("The if statement is true.")
} else if(2 > 1){
  print("The else if statement is true.")
} else{
  print("Neither the if NOR the else if is true.")
}

As you can see, these statements are evaluated in order: first, check the if. Since that was FALSE, we move onto the next statement. We check the else if statement, which is TRUE. Therefore, we don’t check the else block. The important thing to note is that when you have an if/else if/else block, only one of the blocks can execute. Another thing to keep in mind is that you can have any number of else if statements (including 0), and you can have either 0 or 1 else blocks. All of the following constructions are valid:

  • if
  • if/else
  • if/else if
  • if/else if/else if (etc.)
  • if/else if/else if (etc.)/else

Note that if you want to use else if or else, you MUST have one corresponding if statement.

Exercise 2.4 Predict the output of this program! To check your answer, just copy the code and run it. 
print("Green eggs and ham.")

if(1 > 2 | "red" == "blue"){
  print("I do not like green eggs and ham.")
}

if("red" == "green" | 2 > 1){
  print("I do not like them, Sam-I-Am.")
}

# note: when you have a (NOT) in front of a bunch of things,
# you can evaluate from inside-out
if(!(3 != 3 | "pass" == "fail")){
  print("Would you like them here or there?")
}

x = -1
y = 3

if(x < y & x > y){
  print("I would not like them here or there.")
} else if (x < y){
  print("I would not like them anywhere.")
} else if(x > y){
  print("Would you like them in a house?")
} else{
  print("Would you like them with a mouse?")
}

2.5 Loops

Sometimes, we want to do something many times, or we want to do the same operations on a large number of things. To avoid writing out very repetitive blocks of code, we use loops to repeat doing an action many times. We have two main ways to loop: for and while loops.

A VERY IMPORTANT NOTE: in R, you want to avoid using loops. We’ll discuss ways to get around them in the last section. This section therefore is just to introduce basic programming fundamentals. On the other hand, if you can’t think of a way to do something without using a loop, just use a loop – don’t waste time by trying to find a more elegant solution if it isn’t absolutely necessary (look up premature optimization).

2.5.1 While Loops

while loops look a lot like if statements. Instead of just executing something once, while loops will continue executing the code block until the condition is FALSE. Compare the two following blocks of code. In the first, you multiply once; in the second, you multiply until the condition in the while loop is FALSE.

i = 1
if(i < 256){
  i = i*2
  print(i)  # only happens once
}
## [1] 2
i = 1
while(i < 256){
  i = i * 2
  print(i)  # this happens until i = 256
}
## [1] 2
## [1] 4
## [1] 8
## [1] 16
## [1] 32
## [1] 64
## [1] 128
## [1] 256

2.5.2 For Loops

for loops do something for each element in some list (in R and Python, at least). So, it does something to the first element, the second, and so on.

As a example, the following code block multiplies each integer between 1 and 10 (generated by 1:10) by 10. In more detail, i takes on the value 1, and 1*10 is printed (i.e. outputted to the console), then i takes on the value 2, and 2*10 is printed, until the last value is reached. By convention, you use i as the “dummy” counting variable (standing for index). If you have nested for loops (i.e. a loop inside your loop), you’ll commonly see j in the second level and k in the third, etc.

# generate 10 integers, from 1 to 10
for (i in 1:10){
  print(i*10)
}
## [1] 10
## [1] 20
## [1] 30
## [1] 40
## [1] 50
## [1] 60
## [1] 70
## [1] 80
## [1] 90
## [1] 100

for loops are the standard technique for doing something a set number of times.

Exercise 2.6 What happens when you run the following code? Notice that the for loop works, even though you don’t use i at all in the loop.

for (i in 1:5){
  print("USC")
}

However, just to reiterate, avoid looping in R. If you absolutely need to, in a lot of cases it’s better to just got through everything in a vector with a for loop.

3 R-Specific Syntax

R as a programming language is kind of weird, in that there’s a lot of syntax specific to the language to learn. Here’s an overview of the most important concepts.

3.1 Getting Help

If you ever wonder what a package or a function does, type ? before its name (or equivalently, call the help() function). For example, let’s say I’m not sure what the function ifelse() does. Let’s take a look!

?ifelse
# same effect: help(ifelse)

If you run that line of code, you should see help topics on ifelse() pop up in the help window! It turns out the ifelse() function is a vectorized logical operator (more on that later). R documentation tends to be very comprehensive, so always use the question mark!

Another helpful command is args(), which tells you the arguments a function takes if you ever forget. For example, let’s say I wanted to see what order I need to put my parameters for ifelse. Just do the following:

args(ifelse)
## function (test, yes, no) 
## NULL

This tells you very quickly that you need to put your logical operator first, then its output is it’s TRUE, then if its FALSE. You can get the same information by using the ?, but this method is faster if you just want to check the arguments.

Finally, if you run into any errors, you have any further questions, or if you’re not sure how to do something, Google is your friend! Being able to read documentation and search for help online are very important skills in coding jobs (we encourage searching online, as opposed to academic classes, which are really focused on testing your low-level understanding).

3.2 Setting Up the Working Environment

When you first open a document, you want to make sure that your working directory is set properly. That is, when you start reading files into your programs and writing outputs, you want to know which file you’re currently in.

  • To figure out where you are, simply type getwd() into the console (this is equivalent to pwd in Unix).
  • To set your directory, type setwd("DIRECTORY") (this is equivalent to cd, except you need to put quotes around the directory in question).
  • If you want to see the files in the current directory, type list.files() (this is equivalent to ls).

For example, say we have the following directory structure:

Suppose we run getwd(), and we see that we’re in "Users/Kate/Documents/". To run myRscript_1.R, it’s good practice to navigate to your projects directory by running setwd("my_code") (compare to how you would run cd my_code in the terminal – the main difference is that you need the quotes.)

To run myRscript_2.R, run setwd("../Desktop/projects/") (again, compare to cd ../Desktop/projects). The reason you want setwd() is in case your program writes any files, and it makes it easier to read files in.

3.3 Installing Packages

A “package” (also known as a “library”) contains functions, and sometimes data sets, which are not implemented in the base installation of R. Packages are really nice because writing functions is error prone and time consuming, and often these packages have an optimized implementation (i.e. they run faster). Luckily, installing and using packages is very simple.

Say you want to install and use the package tidyverse (it has a lot of useful functions for data analysis; check them out in the Advanced R section). Just include the following lines at the top of your script:

if(!require(tidyverse)){
  install.packages("tidyverse")
}

library(tidyverse)

The if statement just checks if you need to install the package, and library() loads it into your session of R. You only need to install a package once, BUT you must load it into your R environment every time using library() after you restart R.

Remark. If you don’t like this syntax, install and load the pacman package and just use the p_load() function to install and load functions in one go (you’ll see me use this in scripts because I’m lazy):

library(pacman)  # you need to do this first

# this installs the package for you if you don't have it already
# and loads it into your workspace with library
p_load(tidyverse)

Remark. Sometimes, you only need one function from a package, and it’s generally undesirable to load an entire package in just for that one package. In that case, you’ll often see people use the double colon syntax to access a specific function from a package in the form of PACKAGENAME::PACKAGEFUNCTION. For example:

# we don't need run library(pacman)
pacman::p_load(tidyverse)

This syntax also comes in handy for when two packages write two functions with the same name, and it allows you to select which function you want to call. This doesn’t happen very often, but it’s good to know when it does.

3.4 Dataframes

Data frames are two-dimensional representations of data, often with rownames and column names. Let’s look at the mtcars data frame to start with, which is a data set that comes with R. There’s three main ways to examine data tables:

  • head() – this will show the first 6 rows.
  • str() – this will show everything and the data type.
  • glimpse() – this function is implemented in the tidyverse package. It works similarly to str(), but it’s somewhat more informative about the data type. (For example, str() will show num, indicating they are numbers. When you run glimpse() on the mtcars data set, you’ll see <dbl>, which indicates that the numbers are represented non-integer values).

To access a column by name, you would use the $ operator. If you look back on the str() output, you’ll see these dollars signs – these means that they are column elements!

R accesses values by [row, column] order. Note that the square bracket syntax is fairly standard across programming languages to access elements in a list or table. If you leave an element in a bracket empty, it means to select everything (this is most common when you want to select a row or column from a data frame or matrix).

Remark. In other languages (such as C++), accession into tables/data frames use two brackets, so like table[row][column]. Try to not mix them up!

Note that R is 1-indexed, unlike most languages you are probably familiar with (the “index” is the numeric location of the value). This is to say, the top left element is located at (1, 1) and NOT (0, 0).

Therefore, if you want to access by index (the number in which they appear), use the square bracket ([ ]) syntax. So, based on the 1 indexing, dataframe[, 1] is the first column, dataframe[3, ] is the third row, etc.

# dollar sign version
mtcars$mpg
##  [1] 21.0 21.0 22.8 21.4 18.7 18.1 14.3 24.4 22.8 19.2 17.8 16.4 17.3 15.2 10.4
## [16] 10.4 14.7 32.4 30.4 33.9 21.5 15.5 15.2 13.3 19.2 27.3 26.0 30.4 15.8 19.7
## [31] 15.0 21.4
# square bracket version
# since the rows was left empty, it will select all rows
# note that this gets the first column, which is mpg
mtcars[, 1]
##  [1] 21.0 21.0 22.8 21.4 18.7 18.1 14.3 24.4 22.8 19.2 17.8 16.4 17.3 15.2 10.4
## [16] 10.4 14.7 32.4 30.4 33.9 21.5 15.5 15.2 13.3 19.2 27.3 26.0 30.4 15.8 19.7
## [31] 15.0 21.4
# this is the third row
# there is no equivalent "$" way to get rows by name
mtcars[3, ]

R also allows you to select multiple rows and/or columns. You can generate a range of integers using a colon (:), which returns a integer vector. These numbers will then be the rows/columns you select:

mtcars[, 1:3]  # equivalent to mtcars[, c(1,2,3)], the first 3 columns
mtcars[1:3, ] # gets the first three rows, since the columns are unspecified
mtcars[c(2, 6), 4]  # gets the 4th element of rows 2 and 6

3.5 Reading and Writing Files

Often, you want to read in data from a spreadsheet file and to write tables to new files (most programming languages can do this). To read tables, use the read.table() function. To write a data frame, use write.table(). If you want more information about them, type ?read.table and/or args(read.table) into the R console! (This advice applies to all R functions). The most important arguments for read.table() are:

  • file. This is the path to the file you want to read in, and will typically be the first argument. This is a string, so don’t forget your quotes!
  • header: you want to tell R if the first row is a header row with column names or not. If the data you read in looks wonky in R, it’s probably because you need to change this setting. This is a boolean, where TRUE means that the first row is a header, and FALSE otherwise.
  • sep: this tells R what separates columns. For example, in a csv (comma-separated values), you want to type read.table(file.csv, sep=","), while for a tsv (tab-separated values), you should use read.table(file.csv, sep="\t"). Note that sep defaults to "\t", and there is a read.csv() function that is identical to read.table(), but defaults the sep parameter to ",".

Likewise, the argument to write.table() (and equivalently, write.csv()) are:

  • x. This is the object (data frame) you want to write out. It’s called x in the documentation, and will typically be the first argument.
  • file. Again, this is the path and file name you want to write to. Note that this parameter is a string, and remember that you will need to specify the file extension! (So for example, write file="spreadsheet.csv", not file="spreadsheet").
cereal = read.csv("cereal.csv")
write.csv(cereal, "cereal.csv") # nothing actually gets changed

4 Vectors, Vectorized Operators, and Boolean Indexing

4.1 Vectors and Vectorized Operators

Vectors are data structures that are relatively unique to R, and because of this they are often very tricky, but it is extremely helpful to know how to use them well. Vectors are basically lists, except the contents all have to be the same data type (string, numeric, etc). You declare a vector using the c() syntax:

prime_vector = c(2, 3, 5, 7, 11)
prime_vector
## [1]  2  3  5  7 11
char_vector = c("QBIO105", "QBIO401")
char_vector
## [1] "QBIO105" "QBIO401"

As is standard in most programming languages, you can access the element at an index with square brackets, with the same syntax rules with selection as with data frames (again, note the 1-indexing):

prime_vector[1] # this is the first item in the vector!
## [1] 2

Exercise 4.1 Create a vector containing the strings "cyan", "yellow", “magenta”, and "key". Select the middle two values (yellow and magenta).

# code goes here

The reason that vectors are so important is that for loops are extremely slow in R. R has a lot of built-in functions that can be called on vectors (so-called vectorized functions), and they run much faster than coding a for loop. To illustrate the difference, let’s compare two ways to add every element in a vector:

big_vector = 1:10^6  # this contains all integers from 1 to 10^6

for_loop_sum = function(vector){
  x = 0
  for (i in vector){
    x = x + i
  }
  return(x)
}

print(benchmark(
        vectorized = sum(big_vector),
        forloop = for_loop_sum(big_vector), 
        replications = 100))
##         test replications elapsed relative user.self sys.self user.child
## 2    forloop          100   2.941       NA     2.928    0.011          0
## 1 vectorized          100   0.000       NA     0.000    0.000          0
##   sys.child
## 2         0
## 1         0
# make sure the code is doing the same thing
sum(big_vector) == for_loop_sum(big_vector)
## [1] TRUE

As you can see, the first method (using the built-in, vectorized sum function) runs basically instantly, whereas it takes a few seconds to run the for loop in the second method to get the same result (the elapsed column shows the seconds, and relative column shows how much slower the for loop is). The takeaway is to try to use R’s functions over writing your own for loops, since with big data sets it will save a lot of time. Unfortunately, that comes with the burden of remembering the names of the functions.

4.2 Boolean Indexing

Along similar lines to vectorized operators, boolean indexing (also called boolean masking) is a technique to select elements from vectors very quickly. You need two vectors of the same length:

  1. The original vector.
  2. A boolean vector (that is, a vector containing only TRUE and FALSE values).

What happens then is to pass the second vector as an index to the first, which quickly selects the elements marked as TRUE. For example, see the following block of code:

numbers = c(1,2,3)
mask = c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)

numbers[mask]
## [1] 1 3

As you can see, the first and third elements were marked as TRUE, so these two were included, while the middle element was dropped. Boolean indexing becomes useful when you have a large data table and want to pull out certain elements from it. To do so, you need to apply a vectorized operator that returns a boolean value. A common use-case is removing NA values from a data set. In general, you would take the following steps to remove NA values:

  1. Identify which values are NA using is.na().
  2. Use the not operator ! to mark NA values as FALSE.
  3. Reassign the data after applying the mask.

See the following example:

data = c(1, NA, 3, 4, 5, NA)

mask = is.na(data)
mask
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
mask = !is.na(data)
mask  # logical values are flipped
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
data = data[mask]  # you need to reassign the data after selecting, or it will disappear
print(data)  # NAs are gone!
## [1] 1 3 4 5

Since this is a bit long-winded, you can do this all in one line (but if this is a bit confusing, by all means write it out line-by-line).

# this has the same effect as the above chunk
data = c(1, NA, 3, 4, 5, NA)
data
## [1]  1 NA  3  4  5 NA
data = data[!is.na(data)]
data
## [1] 1 3 4 5

4.3 The Very Important ifelse() Function

The ifelse() function is super important for data analysis. As demonstrated in a previous section, it takes in three arguments:

  1. test: this is a boolean vector.
  2. yes: for every TRUE in the vector, replace it with the yes argument.
  3. no: for every FALSE in the vector, replace it with the no argument.

For example, say we have a vector containing integers from 1 to 10 (so 1, 2, …, 10). We want to make a new vector where the odd numbers are replaced with "ODD" and even numbers with "EVEN". Here’s a quick chunk of code that demonstrates this step by step:

nums = 1:10  # 1, 2, ..., 10

# the %% (modulo) takes the remainder after dividing by 2
# then test if it is 0 (even) or not (odd)
is_even = nums %% 2 == 0 
print(is_even)
##  [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
even_and_odds = ifelse(is_even, "EVEN", "ODD")  
print(even_and_odds)
##  [1] "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN"

Usually you’ll just do it in one step (without saving the boolean vector, as reads simpler in most cases):

nums = 1:10

even_and_odds = ifelse(nums %% 2 == 0, "EVEN", "ODD")
print(even_and_odds)
##  [1] "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN" "ODD"  "EVEN"

5 Plotting Data

Plotting data is one of the most powerful R can do, and it’s an extremely important skill to have because visualizing data is fast and gives you an immediate idea of what you’re looking at. You have two main choices with regards to plotting: the base functions or using the package ggplot2, which I prefer because it’s more powerful and it’s prettier. I’ll just show regular plot for this section.

First, let’s see what’s in the mtcars dataset.

?mtcars

Let’s say you really wanted to figure out if there’s a relationship between miles per gallon (mpg) and horsepower (hp). You can quickly visualize this by looking at a scatter plot, with one variable on each axis:

# note: the following code runs equivalently
# and saves you from repeating the dollar sign column accession


# with(mtcars, plot(mpg, hp))

plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$hp)

We want easily see that there’s a negative correlation between horsepower and miles per gallon. However, if you wanted to present this data, you want to make the plot a little more descriptive. You can set the axis labels and title like so:

plot(x = mtcars$mpg, y = mtcars$hp, 
     col = factor(mtcars$vs), # set the color: you need to convert to a factor!
     main = "Cars Horsepower vs. MPG", # set the title
     xlab = "Miles Per Gallon", # set the x-axis label
     ylab = "Horsepower") # set the y-axis label

Other types of plotting follow the same syntax, but there’s many many types of plots out there to visualize different types of data that. Go explore some of the ones below!

  • boxplots (boxplot())
  • histograms (hist())
  • bar plots (barplots())
  • … and many more!

6 (Optional) Advanced R

I briefly mentioned the tidyverse package, which contains a lot of packages that are super useful for data analysis. I’ll mostly be covering the two I use the most, ggplot2 (plotting) and dplyr (data manipulation). I’d recommend reading this section only after you’re comfortable with basic R syntax.

6.1 The tibble data structure

A tibble is just the tidyverse version of the data frame. In terms of functionality, it is basically completely interchangeable with using a regular data frame. However, I prefer tibbles since it prints the columns prettier when you look at it in the console. There’s a few other minor differences that make it less finicky than regular data frames; see the documentation for more details by running ?tibble.

The way you make a tibble is the exact same way as you make a data frame:

column1 = 1:5
column2 = c("red", "green", "blue", "black", "white")
my_tibble = tibble(numbers = column1, colors = column2)
# note: the way you make a data frame is basically the exact same syntax
# my_df = data.frame(numbers = column1, colors = column2)

my_tibble

Likewise, you can convert a data frame into a tibble using as_tbble():

mtcars_tibble = as_tibble(mtcars)

6.2 dplyr

The dplyr package implements functional programming – in a sense, you chain together functions that call other functions to process your data. The key to making this work is the pipe operator, %>%, which is implemented in dplyr. What this does is that it passes the output of the previous function as the first parameter into the next. As a very basic example:

my_nums = 1:10

# this is the same as sum(my_nums)
my_nums %>% sum()
## [1] 55

The reason the pipe operator exists is that when you start nesting functions, things get very ugly. However, first, we need to look at the operations we can use. As usual, we’ll use the mtcars data set to demonstrate.

6.2.1 select

I find this syntax to be a lot less annoying than the way you would handle it in base R, especially when you want to get a large number of rows. To compare:

mtcars_subset = mtcars[, names(mtcars) %in% c("mpg", "cyl", "disp", "hp")]

mtcars_subset

Additionally, there’s other ways to select columns (again, that are in the documentation), making select() even more powerful. This function becomes even more powerful when you combine it with other functions, as seen below.

6.2.2 filter

filter() is the row analogue to select(). Recall how we first showed you how to perform this by boolean indexing:

# get the cars with mpg 20 and greater
mtcars_subset = mtcars[mtcars$mpg >= 20, ]

mtcars_subset

With filter(), it looks quite similar, but more readable:

mtcars_subset = mtcars %>%
  filter(mpg >= 20)

mtcars_subset

Now, what if we want to select cars with mpg >= 20 AND only get the rows we did before. With normal data frame operations, it starts to get messy:

# you can select rows and columns separately, but that's even more typing
mtcars_subset = mtcars[mtcars$mpg >= 20,
                       names(mtcars) %in% c("mpg", "cyl", "disp", "hp")]

mtcars_subset

With the pipe and tidyverse, it’s much cleaner and more obvious what you’re trying to do:

mtcars_subset = mtcars %>%
  select(mpg, cyl, disp, hp) %>%
  filter(mpg >= 20)

mtcars_subset

6.2.3 mutate

mutate() is a function used to either change existing columns or to create a new columns. The base R way to do is looks something as follows.

# you need to explicitly make a new copy
mtcars_new = mtcars
mtcars_new$mpg_quality = ifelse(mtcars$mpg >= 20, "good", "bad")

mtcars_new

With mutate(), we can simplify things a bit:

mtcars_new = mtcars %>%
  mutate(mpg_quality = ifelse(mpg >= 20, "good", "bad"))

mtcars_new

Furthermore, we can add or edit more than one column in one call:

mtcars_new = mtcars %>%
  mutate(mpg_quality = ifelse(mpg >= 20, "good", "bad"), # our previous statement
         hp = scale(hp), # modify hp by standardizing to mean 0, variance 1
         hp_new = ifelse(hp >= 0, "high", "low"))  # we can use the newly create column to make another

mtcars_new

The really useful thing is that we can put all these together in a single call, which really makes things easier to read:

mtcars_subset = mtcars %>%
  select(mpg, hp) %>%
  filter(mpg >= 20) %>%
  mutate(mpg_hp_ratio = mpg/hp) %>%
  arrange(-mpg_hp_ratio) # arrange is basically order

mtcars_subset

6.2.4 summarise and groupby

Finally, it’s pretty common that we want to summarize our data by a certain attribute. group_by() followed by summarise() allows us to do so. For example, to summarize mpg by the number of cylinders:

mean_var_summary = mtcars %>%
  group_by(cyl) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(mpg), variance = var(mpg)) # summarize by mean and variance

mean_var_summary

As you can see, there’s a lot of functions that are helpful for processing your data. Feel free to either use basic R functionality or tidyverse in your exercises!

6.3 ggplot

I briefly showed the ggplot() syntax, but this is a slightly more in-depth explanation on how to use this plotting package. As mentioned previously, the way you typically make a plot is that you define the variables that you want to plot, then layer on plot elements. The syntax is a bit intimidating at first, but once you get familiar it gets much more intuitive. (I personally only use ggplot and have no idea how to use base R plotting except in the most basic ways)

6.3.1 qplot

By the way, if you’re familiar with basic R plotting, the qplot() function uses the same syntax, but creates prettier plots. For instance:

library(patchwork)  # this lets you display two plots side by side with the +
## 
## Attaching package: 'patchwork'
## The following object is masked from 'package:cowplot':
## 
##     align_plots
p1 = qplot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$hp)
p2 = qplot(mtcars$mpg)

p1 + p2
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

This is nice to explore variables, but it’s harder to make prettier plots.

6.3.2 Scatter Plots

Scatter plots tend to be the simplest and most common, so I’ll start here. We pass in the data to plot, then in aes() we define what to put on the axes.

p = ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
  geom_point()

p

We can color the points by defining the color aes:

# we want to make cyl a factor
# otherwise, it's a numeric value, so we get a gradient
p = ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(cyl)))

p

And we can plop a line on top with the geom_smooth() layer:

# we want to make cyl a factor
# otherwise, it's a numeric value, so we get a gradient
p = ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(cyl))) + 
  geom_smooth(se = F, method = "lm")  # hide the error margin, draw the linear regression line

p
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Finally, we can split the data points using facet_grid():

# we want to make cyl a factor
# otherwise, it's a numeric value, so we get a gradient
p = ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(cyl))) + 
  facet_grid(cols = vars(cyl)) + 
  geom_smooth(se = F, method = "lm")  # hide the error margin, draw the linear regression line

p
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There’s a whole bunch more functionality and different plot types, but I’ll leave that exploring to you.

6.3.3 Plotting Error Bars

Plotting error bars is important for presenting your data, though there’s no standard as to what an error bar represents. Here, we’ll just use our mtcars summary from last time and display the error as the standard deviation of the mean. In publications, you’ll probably most frequently see error bars representing confidence intervals or standard error of the mean. The confidence intervals are probably the most informative, though they can be a bit mathy and more difficult to calculate (it requires a lot of stats knowledge).

# calculate the standard deviation from the variance (is sqrt(var))
plot_data = mean_var_summary %>% 
  mutate(stdev = sqrt(variance), 
         cyl = factor(cyl))

# create a bar plot with geom_col()
# we use fill instead of color for barplots
# we calculate the position of errors bars by +- standard deviation
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = cyl, y = mean, fill = cyl)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean - stdev, ymax = mean + stdev, width = 0.2))

6.4 Ways to write loops in R

R has alternatives to writing for loops; namely, there is a family of apply functions that, well, apply a function across a vector. These have the advantage of returning a vector, but they aren’t actually much faster than a regular loop. There’s four functions you’ll probably use:

  • apply: this works over a matrix. It’s mostly used if you want to apply a function over rows, rather than columns (it accepts an additional argument, MARGIN).
  • lapply: this returns a list (i.e. list-apply).
  • sapply: this returns a vector or matrix, determined automatically (i.e. simple-apply). I personally prefer this one.
  • mapply: this goes across two or more iterable objects at the same time. The syntax is slightly different, with mapply(FUNC, X, Y, Z, ...), where X, Y, Z, are the iterable objects.

These functions use the following basic syntax (again, with the exception of mapply):

apply(X, function(x))

where X is some kind of vector/list/dataframe, and function is some function. The x passed to the function is a stand-in for the values that are being iterated over by the apply function. Note that you can define your own function as part of the apply function. For example, if you had a data frame and wanted to get both the mean and variance of each column and put 0s for categorical variables, you can do the following (on the iris data set):

vals1 = sapply(iris, function(x){  # you can define your own function here!
  if (is.numeric(x)){
    return(c(mean(x), var(x)))
  } else{
    return(c(0, 0))
  }
})

vals1
##      Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## [1,]    5.8433333   3.0573333     3.758000   1.1993333       0
## [2,]    0.6856935   0.1899794     3.116278   0.5810063       0
#### for loop version:
vals2 = matrix(nrow = 2, ncol = 5, dimnames = list(NULL, names(iris)))

for(i in 1:ncol(iris)){
  x = iris[, i]
  if (is.numeric(x)){
    vals2[, i] = c(mean(x), var(x))
  } else{
    vals2[, i] = c(0, 0)
  }
}

vals2  # equivalent to vals1
##      Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## [1,]    5.8433333   3.0573333     3.758000   1.1993333       0
## [2,]    0.6856935   0.1899794     3.116278   0.5810063       0

Syntactically, it’s considered superior in R to do the first version, as it’s easier to read, doesn’t involve declaring extra variables ahead of time (that matrix line looks real ugly), and overall is more flexible. Practically, you’ll probably see the for loop version more, as most people who use R come from another language, and the for loop syntax is more familiar (the run time isn’t much different in any case). Use whichever syntax you prefer, but it’s good to be able to understand code that other people wrote. However, it’s still best to use an built-in function.

That’s about it for now – the best way to learn is by practicing!
